;; **
;;; ## Linear Dynamical Systems
;;; 
;;; A Linear Dynamical System (LDS) is a state-space (i.e. time series) model with observations @@\v{y}\_t@@ and latent variables @@\v{x}\_t@@, 
;;; @@\begin{align}
;;; p(\v{y},\v{x})
;;; &=
;;; p(\v{y}\_1 \,|\, \v{x}\_1) p(\v{x}\_1)
;;; \prod\_{t=2}^T
;;; p(\v{y}\_t \,|\, \v{x}\_t) 
;;; p(\v{x}\_t \,|\, \v{x}\_{t-1}).
;;; \end{align}@@
;;; 
;;; In an LDS, the likelihoods @@p(\v{y}\_t \,|\, \v{x}\_t)@@, conditional distributions @@p(\v{x}\_t \,|\, \v{x\_{t-1}})@@, and prior @@p(\v{x}\_1)@@ all take the form of (multivariate) normals. Posterior inference can be performed analytically via a forward-backward (message-passing) calculation, that relies on the fact that any marginal of a multivariate normal is itself normally distributed. In this worksheet we compare posterior estimates obtained via sampling (with Sequential Monte Carlo) to the exact results obtained from a Kalman Smoother.
;;; 
;;; 
;; **

;; **
;;; ### Graphical Model
